?def: A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to aztreonam, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to rotenone, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.

A pathogen host interaction (molecular function??) phenotype in which the binding of one protein to a protein complex is abnormal. The protein whose binding to the protein complex is affected may be encoded by the mutated gene, or may be encoded by a different gene.

A pathogen host interaction phenotype which affects the morphology of the pathogen or the host during pathogen colonization of the host. This relates to the pathogen colonization of the body, tissues, or cells of the host organism.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to epoxyconazole, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.

A pathogen host interaction phenotype which affects the host reproductive process within the host when a pathogen is present. The production of new individuals that contain some portion of genetic material inherited from one or more parent organisms (GO:0000003).
A pathogen host interaction phenotype, in which the level of pathogen RNA usually present during infection is higher than normal.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to emamectin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to aureobasidin A, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to prochloraz, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A single organism cellular process phenotype in which vacuolar transport is abnormal.

A pathogen host interaction colonization phenotype in which the ability of the pathogen to move directionally within the host organism is gained (pathogen migration was absent within the host and is now present).
A host reproductive phenotype with pathogen where the process of host seed development is abnormal (GO:0048316).
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to D-cycloserine, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.

A single organism phenotype that affects the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of secondary metabolites, the compounds that are not necessarily required for growth and maintenance of cells, and are often unique to a taxon.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to carbapenems, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.

A single organism phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the ability of the organism to form autophagosomes is abolished (they were present and are now absent) (GO:0005776).
A single species cell phenotype in which the amount of deoxynivalenol measured in a cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to camptothecin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype, in which the level of pathogen RNA usually present during infection is lower than normal.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to ketoconazole, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A single species cell phenotype in which the amount of protein measured in a cell differs from normal. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.
A single species phenotype where the dispersal of asexual spores is abnormal (FAO:0000023).
A single species individual organism phenotype where the accumulation of coloring matter in a cell is normal.
The pathogen effector entity has an increased ability to activate host defence.
The pathogen effector entity has a decreased ability to suppress host defence.
A single species phenotype that is observed at the level of an individual organism.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype in which the pathogen biosynthesis of deoxynivalenol is abnormal (i.e. different than the wild type).
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to pentamidine, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A reproductive morphology phenotype where the size of the asexual spore is decreased.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype, in which the pathogen produced deoxynivalenol usually present during infection is present as normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

A phenotype where the ability of a pathogen, to produce an infectious disease in another organism is unaffected (i.e the same as wild-type, this could be pathogenicity present or pathogenicity absent).
A phenotype that shows detectable differences from normal at the level of an individual cell.

A single organism phenotype that affects a double-membrane-bounded compartment that engulfs endogenous cellular material as well as invading microorganisms to target them to the lytic vacuole/lysosome for degradation as part of macroautophagy (GO:0005776).
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to kanamycin A, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to vancomycin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A single species cell phenotype in which fungal hyphae form an increased number of branches.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to ofloxacin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A reproductive phenotype in which the occurrence of asexual spore formation happens sooner than normal.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to farnesol, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.

A phenotype where the degree to which a pathogen (species or strain) is able to cause infectious disease in another organism is abolished when observed in an interaction with a pathogen mutant which was previously engineered to gain pathogenicity.

A pathogen host interaction phenotype which affects the localization of a polysaccharide in a pathogen or host cell is abnormal. This includes any process in which a polysaccharide is transported to, or maintained in, a specific location. (GO:0033037).

A pathogen reproductive phenotype within host where the pathogen sexual reproduction process, in which new individuals are produced by combining the genetic material of two gametes, which may come from two organisms or from a single organism is normal (indistinguishable from wild type) (GO:0019953).
A pathogen host interaction phenotype, in which the level of host produced callose deposition usually present during infection is higher than normal.
The pathogen effector entity has gained the ability to suppress host defence.
A single species phenotype where the localization of a structure or substance in a cell is abnormal.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to gramicidin D, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to caspofungin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.

A single organism (molecular function??) phenotype in which occurrence of RNA binding by a gene product is abnormal, when a gene or the bound RNA sequence is mutated. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.
(Required for successful infection of the host species). The ability of an organism to activate or suppress host defences to enable infectious disease. (Irrespective of the host genotype).
A pathogen entry into host phenotype in which pathogen penetration into the body, tissues, or cells of the host organism is absent.
A reproductive phenotype where the process of sexual sporulation, the formation of spores from the products of meiosis, is normal (GO:0034293).
A phenotype in which a specific transport process is abnormal in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle.

A pathogen (molecular function??) phenotype in which the binding of one protein to a protein complex is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). The protein whose binding to the protein complex is assayed may be encoded by the mutated gene, or may be encoded by a different gene.
A pathogen growth with host phenotype in which the formation of the pathogen penetration structure is normal (i.e indistinguishable from wild type).
A reproductive process phenotype in which the first meiotic nuclear division is abnormal (GO:0007127).
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to vancomycin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to florfenicol, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A single species cell phenotype in which the amount of chitin measured in the spore is higher than normal

A single species population phenotype in which a population shows decreased resistance to a chemical stimulus. Resistance to a chemical is usually measured by determining the maximum concentration of the chemical at which a population grows and divides. Typically, populations are deemed sensitive to a chemical if they stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of the chemical that allows wild type populations to grow.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to terbinafine, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A host morphology phenotype where the size of the host is normal (indistinguishable from wild type) during pathogen invasion.

A single species metabolic cellular process phenotype in which the formation of reactive oxygen species (any molecules or ions formed by the incomplete one-electron reduction of oxygen) is unaltered.(GO:1903409)
A single species colony morphology phenotype where the colony is more rugose (wrinkled; corrugated) than normal.
A single species cell phenotype in which the amount of a specific substance measured in a cell is lower than normal.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype, in which the host immune response protease activity is inhibited by the pathogen.
A single organism metabolic process phenotype in which the occurrence of lipid droplet degradation (lipolysis) is decreased (GO:0016042 and GO:0005811).
A single species population phenotype in which a population grows normally (i.e. indistinguishably from wild type).
An single species phenotype in which an asexual spore lyses, i.e. the plasma membrane ruptures and cytoplasm is lost.
A population growth phenotype in which organism growth is decreased relative to normal in a medium containing oleic acid as the carbon source.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to novobiocin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A reproductive morphology phenotype where the size of the sexual spore is decreased.
A single species cell population phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is faster than normal.

A single species molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one protein to a protein complex is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). The protein whose binding to the protein complex is assayed may be encoded by the mutated gene, or may be encoded by a different gene.
A pathogen host interaction colonization phenotype in which the occurrence of the directional movement of the pathogen within the host organism is decreased compared to normal.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to sulfanilamide, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A pathogen host phenotype in which the vegetative growth or proliferation of the pathogen inside the host is present.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to propiconazole, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A single species cell phenotype in which the amount of protein measured in a cell is lower than normal. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to tigecycline, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A reproductive phenotype where asexual spores are present (FAO:0000017). The product of meiosis.
A pathogen growth with host phenotype in which the pathogen penetration into the host is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to tunicamycin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to flucytosine, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype in which the localization of an RNA in a cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A pathogen host interaction phenotype in which a specific transport process is abnormal.
A reproductive morphology phenotype where the shape of the asexual spore is abnormal.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to isoniazid, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A single species phenotype that affects the localization of a structure or substance in a cell.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to cefazolin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.

A pathogen host interaction phenotype in which the localization of a polysaccharide in a pathogen or host cell is abnormal. This includes any process in which a polysaccharide is transported to, or maintained in, a specific location. (GO:0033037).
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to posaconazole, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to clarithromycin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.

A single species phenotype where the asexual reproductive developmental process whose specific outcome is the progression of structures that will be used in the process of creating new individuals, from their formation to the mature structures is abnormal (GO:0048608).
A reproductive phenotype in which the occurrence of sexual spore formation happens later than normal.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to fenhexamid, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A pathogen host phenotype in which the vegetative growth or proliferation of the pathogen inside the host is abolished (it was present as is now absent).
A single species population phenotype in which the population grows abnormally during the yeast-form lifecycle stage.
A single species cell phenotype in which the amount of pyocyanin measured in a cell is lower than normal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one pathogen protein to one host protein occurs to a greater extent than normal.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to rapamycin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to nisin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to triclosan, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to amikacin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to hygromycin B, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to bacitracin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to minocycline, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A single species colony morphology phenotype where the size of the population is  decreased.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to sodium chloride, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth. (CHEBI:26710).
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to caspofungin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to cycloheximide, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A single species reproductive phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of sexual sporulation structures is fewer than normal.

A pathogen host interaction (molecular function??) phenotype in which a gene product that normally binds to a specific DNA sequence instead binds to a different sequence when a gene is mutated. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

A pathogen host interaction (cellular process???) phenotype in which endocytosis is abnormal. Endocytosis is a vesicle-mediated transport process in which cells take up external materials or membrane constituents by the invagination of a small region of the plasma membrane to form a new membrane-bounded vesicle. A phenotype may affect endocytosis of all cargoes, or of specific cargo such as a particular protein.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to micafungin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to plumbagin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to actinomycin D, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to cefotaxime, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A population growth phenotype in which organism growth is decreased relative to normal in a medium containing erucic acid as the carbon source.

A pathogen host interaction phenotype that affects the chemical reactions and pathways involving those compounds which are formed as a part of the normal anabolic and catabolic processes. These processes take place in most, if not all, cells of the organism.

A single species phenotype where the asexual reproductive developmental process whose specific outcome is the progression of structures that will be used in the process of creating new individuals, from their formation to the mature structures is normal (GO:0048608).
A pathogen reproductive phenotype within host where the pathogen asexual spores are absent (FAO:0000023).
A reproductive phenotype where the process of asexual sporulation, the formation of spores derived from the products of an asexual cell division, is normal (GO:0030436).
A pathogen host interaction phenotype where the pathogen induces a pH decrease within the host cell or cellular component.
A single species cellular process phenotype in which the number of septa produced during hyphae formation is increased.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to tebuconazole, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to abamectin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to gentamycin C1, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype where the pathogen induces a pH increase within the host cell or cellular component.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to alexidine, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to doxycycline, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype, in which the level of host RNA usually present during infection is higher than normal.

A pathogen host interaction phenotype that affects the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in many of the chemical changes of compounds that are not necessarily required for growth and maintenance of cells, and are often unique to a taxon. In multicellular organisms secondary metabolism is generally carried out in specific cell types, and may be useful for the organism as a whole. In unicellular organisms, secondary metabolism is often used for the production of antibiotics or for the utilization and acquisition of unusual nutrients.
A single species cell morphology phenotype where hyphal filaments are wavy.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to anidulafungin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to sparfloxacin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to tetracycline, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to pyrazinecarboxamide, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A cellular process phenotype in which the rate, or speed, of asexual spore germination is decreased.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype that affects a host immune system process during pathogen infection (GO:0002376).
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to trovafloxacin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to carbendazim, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.

A single species pathogen growth phenotype in which the  ability of the pathogen to  form a specialized penetration structure is abolished when assessed for penetration ability on a given experimental substance/membrane.
An single species phenotype in which an asexual spore does not lyse, i.e. the plasma membrane ruptures and cytoplasm is lost.
A single species hyphal colony morphology phenotype where the aerial height of the filamentous colony is increased.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to fluconazole, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A single organism cellular process phenotype in which protein transport is abnormal.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype, in which the level of pathogen protein usually present during infection is lower than normal.
A pathogen colonization of host phenotype where the vegetative growth or proliferation of the pathogen on the host surface is present.

A pathogen host interaction phenotype where the size of the pathogen vacuoles are larger than normal during host colonization. This relates to the pathogen colonization of the body, tissues, or cells of the host organism.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to pyrimethanil, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A single organism phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells contain fewer autophagosomes than normal (GO:0005776).
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to fusidic acid, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype that affects DNA binding. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.
A single organism cell population phenotype that reflects the proportion of the population that survive and develop normally.
A pathogen host interaction colonization phenotype in which the occurrence of the directional movement of the pathogen within the host organism happens sooner than normal.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to methicillin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype where the pathogen reproductive process within the host is abnormal.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to doxycycline, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.

A single species phenotype where the asexual reproductive developmental process whose specific outcome is the progression of structures that will be used in the process of creating new individuals, from their formation to the mature structures is abolished (it was present and is now absent) (GO:0048608).
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to chlortetracycline, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to ciprofloxacin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A single species cellular process phenotype in which the rate, or speed, of germ tube formation is decreased.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to tobramycin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype in which the toxin biosynthetic process is normal (i.e. same as the wild type).
A single organism phenotype which is abnormal (i.e. different than wild-type).
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to nitrofurantoin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to penicillin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to triadimefon, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype where the process of host tissue PCD modulated by the pathogen is present (GO:0034053).
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to spectinomycin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to tridemorph, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.

A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to nystatin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to ampicillin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to furazolidone, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A single species phenotype that affects the binding of one protein to another. The relevant proteins may include the one encoded by the mutated gene, or may both be encoded by different genes.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype, which affects a pathogen induced host oxidative burst (GO:0002679).
A population growth phenotype which cells show increased sensitivity to iron ion starvation.
A single species population phenotype affecting the morphology of a colony growing in filamentous form.

A single organism (molecular function??) phenotype in which DNA binding by a gene product does not occur, when a gene or the bound DNA sequence is mutated. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.
A single species pathogen penetration phenotype in which pathogen penetration of a given experimental substance/membrane is absent.
A single organism phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the size, shape, or structure of lipid droplets is abnormal.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to fludioxonil, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to netilmicin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.

A single species pathogen growth phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of pathogen penetration stuctures are increased when assessed for penetration ability on a given experimental substance/membrane.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to potassium chloride, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to azoxystrobin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to cercosporamide, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.

A single species metabolic cellular process phenotype in which the formation of reactive oxygen species (any molecules or ions formed by the incomplete one-electron reduction of oxygen) is decreased.(GO:1903409)
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to triclosan, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A single species hyphal colony morphology phenotype where the aerial height of the filamentous colony is decreased.
A single species individual organism phenotype where the accumulation of melanin in a cell is decreased.

A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to thiabendazole, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A single species cell phenotype in which the amount of gliotoxin measured in a cell is too low to detect.
A single species phenotype where the dispersal of sexual spores is normal (FAO:0000017).

A cell signaling pathway phenotype where the host pattern recognition receptor signalling pathway is directly induced by a pathogen. This can include any series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a pattern recognition receptor (PRR) binding to a pathogen-derived physiological ligand. PRR ligands are usually referred to as pathogen-associated molecular pattern (PAMPs) or microbe-associated molecular pattern (MAMPs), structures conserved among microbial species (GO:0002221).
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to bleomycin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to captan, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to verapamil, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to imipenem, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to streptomycin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A single species individual organism phenotype where the accumulation of melanin in a cell is increased.
A single species individual organism phenotype where the accumulation of coloring matter in an asexual spore cell is altered.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to netilmicin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one pathogen protein to one host protein occurs for a shorter time than normal.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to nikkomycin Z, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A cell phenotype in which the amount of a specific substance measured in a cell within a pathogen host interaction differs from normal.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype, in which a pathogen effects a change in the structure or processes of its host organism (GO:0044003).
A pathogen host interaction phenotype in which the pathogen biosynthesis of deoxynivalenol is normal (i.e. same as the wild type).
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to cyclosporine A, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype in which the localization of a pathogen protein to the host chloroplast is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A single organism phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the nucleus is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type)(GO:0034504).

A single organism phenotype in which the localization of an RNA in a cell is abnormal. An RNA may be observed in a place where it is not normally found, absent from a place where it is normally found, or both.
A phenotype that affects a process of cellular component organization, i.e. the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a cellular component, that occurs at the cellular level.
A single species phenotype in which the pathogen's ability to contine to grow after penetration of a given experimental substance/membrane in an in vitro assay is absent.
A phenotype in which a specific cellular process is abnormal.

A single species molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of carbohydrate binding by a gene product is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). The relevant gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.
The host defences activated by the pathogen are altered compared to the wild type interaction

A single species molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one protein to a protein complex is abnormal. The protein whose binding to the protein complex is affected may be encoded by the mutated gene, or may be encoded by a different gene.
A single species pathogen molecular function phenotype in which pathogen chitin fragment binding by a pathogen gene product is decreased.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype where the morphology of the host plasma membrane has increased blebbing during pathogen invasion.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype which affects the pathogen morphology during host colonization. This relates to the pathogen colonization of the body, tissues, or cells of the host organism.
A single species cell phenotype in which the amount of a specific substance measured in a cell is higher than normal.
A single organism phenotype that affects the localization of an RNA in a cell.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to minocycline, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A pathogen growth with host phenotype in which the pathogen specialized host penetration structure is absent.
A single species population phenotype where the morphology of a colony growing in filamentous form is normal (indistinguishable from wild type).
A phenotype in which a specific cellular process is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

A single species colony morphology phenotype where the colony is smoother than normal.
A cell phenotype in which the amount of a specific substance measured in a pathogen or host cell is too low to detect.
A single organism phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the size of lipid droplets is increased.

A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to gatifloxacin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.

A pathogen host interaction phenotype which affects either the pathogen or host reproductive process. The production of new individuals that contain some portion of genetic material inherited from one or more parent organisms (GO:0000003).
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to ethambutol, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A single species individual organism phenotype where the accumulation of melanin in a cell is absent.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to streptomycin sulfate, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype, in which the host pH value during infection differs from normal.

A single species pathogen growth phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of pathogen penetration stuctures are decreased when assessed for penetration ability on a given experimental substance/membrane.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to streptomycin sulfate, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.

A reproductive phenotype where the process of endospore formation, in which a cell gives rise to an endospore, a dormant, highly resistant spore with a thick wall that forms within the mother cell is abnormal. Endospores are produced by some low G+C Gram-positive bacteria in response to harsh conditions. (GO:0034301)
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to virginiamycin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A single species phenotype where the dispersal of sexual spores is abnormal (FAO:0000017).
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to nitrofurantoin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A reproductive process phenotype in which the first meiotic nuclear division is normal (GO:0007127).

A single organism (molecular function??) phenotype in which occurrence of DNA binding by a gene product is abnormal, when a gene or the bound DNA sequence is mutated. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to itraconazole, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to 4-aminosalicylic acid, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.

A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to ethionamide, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to meropenem, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A singe species cell phenotype in which the amount of RNA measured in a cell is lower than normal. Total RNA or a specific RNA, such as the mRNA transcribed from a gene of interest, may be affected.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype, in which the level of pathogen produced deoxynivalenol usually present during infection is higher than normal.
A phenotype where the process of host tissue PCD modulated by the pathogen is absent (GO:0034053).
A single organism cellular process phenotype in which protein transport is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

A single species population growth phenotype in which a cell requires a particular organic compound, which is not required by a wild-type cell for its growth. Auxotrophy usually results from a cell's inability to synthesize the compound.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to colistin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A single species hyphal colony morphology phenotype where the aerial height of the filamentous colony is normal (indistinguishable from wild type).

A single species colony morphology phenotype where the size of the population is normal (indistinguishable from wild type).
A single species cell phenotype in which the amount of pyocyanin measured in a cell is higher than normal.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to tobramycin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased sensitivity to ertapenem, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A pathogen entry into host phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of pathogen penetration into the body, tissues, or cells of the host organism begins sooner than normal.
A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to carboxin, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
A population phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of sexual spores is increased.
A single species hyphal colony phenotype where the shape of the colony is abnormal.
A pathogen growth with host phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of pathogen penetration stuctures near the host are increased.

A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to actinomycin D, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.

A reproductive process phenotype in which a cell does not proceed normally through a meiotic cell cycle (GO:0051321).
A single species population growth phenotype in which cells show increased sensitivity to a stress.

A pathogen reproductive phenotype within host in which the frequency of occurrence of asexual spores is normal  (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

A pathogen host interaction phenotype, in which the host immune signaling pathway is induced by a pathogen.

A phenotype in which a population of a single-species shows increased resistance to chlorothalonil, manifested as an affect on the extent of population growth.
